<p>Based on a transect from north to south, the warming trend in 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm59">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>min</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> changed from high to low (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="ijerph-16-01504-f003">Figure 3</xref>). For 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm60">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>max</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, this increase reduced both from north to south and from west to east. For some stations, there was actually a cooling trend for 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm61">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>max</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. Most of these stations were located in northern China, where irrigation has been implemented to enhance agriculture. Presumably, the evapotranspiration during summer contributed to the obvious decrease in 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm62">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>max</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> in this area [
 <xref rid="B23-ijerph-16-01504" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>]. In general, either 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm63">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>min</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> rose at a faster pace than 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm64">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>max</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> or 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm65">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>min</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> kept increasing, whereas 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm66">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>T</mi>
      <mrow>
       <mi>max</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> decreased. As a consequence, SDTR decreased for most stations, although a few stations had pronounced increases in SDTR.
</p>
